{"key":"processedPost-16285705","value":{"id":16285705,"first":16284779,"last":16287867,"when":1338006217,"utime":"05/26/12 07:23 AM","content":"You're mistaking what field capacity is.&nbsp; It's a measure for bulk substrates where you squeeze a handful and get a small stream of water out.&nbsp; If grains were that wet, they'd never colonize.<br /><br />If one put grain or brf jars in an oven to sterilize, as soon as the interior reached 100C, the moisture would be rapidly escaping, because water can not survive in the liquid state above that temperature unless under pressure.&nbsp; Mason jar lids are designed to hold a vacuum, but not pressure.&nbsp; They would vent and let all the water out.&nbsp; By the time 60 minutes passed, the substrate within the jars would be bone dry.<br />RR","title":"Re: Baking rather than boiling or pressure cooking","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}